text: 1. This movie tackles racism. 2. This movie is created by the people who worked on Bolt and Wreck-It-Ralph, the prior film being great and the latter being amazing. 3. This movie will be considerably darker than recent Disney films, as stated by the directors themselves. 4. This movie is giving us male and female characters that aren't romantically involved and instead form a deep and meaningful friendship, which is something that is barely seen. 5. This movie, regardless of it's story, looks absolutely stunning and beautiful. 6. Idris Elba, J.K Simmons, and Octavia Spencer are all lending their voices to this movie, and while voice actors/actresses don't make a movie, we're still being given truly talented ACTORS to bring these voices to life (not regular famous people who can't voice act and are there simply to make the movie sell).  7. The movie's main song "Try Everything" is sung by Shakira, and has lyrics made by Sia and Starset.   Yet people are complaining about how "furry" this movie is, completely disregarding that Disney turned Robin Hood into a fox once.

text: Alright, let's discuss the elephant in the room. Yes this is obviously a movie that has fan service for furries. Now this isn't a bad thing, but hopefully it won't blind the message of the movie. What I can predict is that this movie will target social issues such as sexism and racism (Specism?) but I really hope this movie stays on the subject of trusting other people that you do not know. I noticed at 0:29 that there is obvious fear between the two species shown riding together. Two different kinds of animals, two different kind of stories. Since one of the species is known as a predator and the other prey, the prey don't trust the predator therefore adding a lack of trust. Sound familiar? I hope this movie doesn't just say "everyone trust each other and get along", but instead actually try to find a way to resolve the issue in a manner where it stays solved.

If she, the first female in the force, can make it that means the doors are blown wide open for the other possible female recruits.   So maybe this is a speciesism thing after all. text: You people are insane. This looks amazing. It's creative, it's nicely animated, and I ALREADY enjoy the Dynamic between Judy and Nick.  Just because it has anthropomorphic animals, doesn't mean it's bad. Micky Mouse is an Anthropomorphic animal. Bugs Bunny is an Anthropomorphic animal. There are PLENTY of movies with Anthropomorphic animals.  If you hate animals, then, sure, I understand why you wouldn't like this film. But all the rest of you are just trying to piss off the furry community by hating on this film, because a portion of them watch porn. If this film came out way back in the day, you'd leave it alone, but right now it's like a trend to make fun of furries. Good for you, go pet yourself on the back.  ((Before anyone asks, I'm not a furry myself)). Either way, this movie looks amazing for anyone who likes animals and animated flicks.

text: (SPOILER ALERT) *If you haven't seen the movie, don't read this comment!!!   As a Disney fan, I have noticed that Disney movies these days are reusing the concept of the "good, cute innocent-looking fellow" being the bad guy. Let's start with Lotso Huggin Bear; a cute, huggable strawberry-scented bear, who has plans on overthrowing innocent toys to the Caterpillar room and reigning over Sunnyside. King Candy; a comical and quirky, funny-looking king, who is actually Turbo and has plans to take over Sugar Rush, with the deletion of Vanellope's identity and death of Ralph. Hans; a handsome, regal-looking prince, who has plans on killing Anna and Elsa to reign over Arendelle. Professor Callaghan; a smart, wise-looking and compassionate professor, who has plans on killing Alistar Krei because of her daughter's (assumed) death, caused by Krei's project. And lastly, our newest addition to this "villain line" is Bellwether; a small, cute and adorable lamb/sheep, who has plans on taking over Zootopia by framing Lionheart's reputation by turning evolved predators into savage creatures, with the use of her "Nighthowler" serum. Who will be the next villain, disguised in a good,cute innocent-looking fellow? ......... (if I forgot someone, please note)

text: Hello Walt Disney, This is a one of the creators of an animation similar to this. Our show, Animalentary, is very similar and does have a different premise and story. But we did not know that Zootopia existed before we made the animations.Our show is also about Humanoid animals living together, but it's something different, its more like a cliche school thing. We wrote the scripts, storyboards and started planning for the future episodes, but with the copyright system., we may not make this animation real. We want to make it real, I just want to see how people react to the show and not call it a ripoff of this. My friends were excited to play a part in a big project, and we really want the animation to be done by the end of our summer. We appreciate and like your movie, and we hope you allow us to upload something similar to this but not too similar.  Sincerely, The Admin

text: Just watched this movie, Loved it, but the only problem was that the people in front of me had a kid that always stood on his chair and looked at me, making me uncomfortable as well as blocking my view. He also wouldn't shut up. Opening, the kid was screaming. Explosion, the kid was screaming. Emotional moment that would have been very heartwarming, that same kid was screaming. he also ran up and down the stairs and played with other kids. This ruined the movie for me, but it was still amazing. To Disney, good job. To parents, CONTROL YOUR CHILDREN OR LEAVE!! I don't care how old your kid is or the fact that it's a kid movie, it is your responsibility to know if your child would make noises before buying the tickets. Everyone else around you paid just as much money as you did to watch a movie, not listen to your screaming children, be considerate. To Krikorian Premiere Theaters, please have an employee go up the stairs every once in a while to make sure these inconsiderate parent don't ruin everything for the rest of us, Harkins does it and so can you. I'm now going to try to forget as much about this movie as possible so I could actually enjoy it on DVD without little children screaming in the background.

text: This has to be the only time that Rule 34 has lead me to something, and not the other way around. This actually looks really good, and it's a flattering look at the Furry subculture. Believe it or not, we're not just in it for the porn. These are creative designs that have good comedic and emotional potential. I mean, go back a few years and a movie like this wouldn't have even been thought viable, not even by the Furries.   I won't deny there's a large pornographic element to the subculture, but I do think it can be seen as respectable by the mainstream one day.

text: It's funny how things play out, I had absolutely no intentions of seeing zootopia I thought it was just another bland overly ridiculous Disney movie, but since I just wanted something to do and decided to see KFP3 (utter waste of money) they played a trailer I hadn't seen before that peaked my interest in Zootopia. So since KFP3 was a disappointment I thought I'd try my luck with Zootopia, and let me just tell you the preconceived notions I had about this movie were dead wrong, my mind was BLOWN by the way the incorporated our reality and it's social issues into this movie without directly stating that's what it was. The maturity and deeper message was expertly conveyed through storyline, I'm really glad I saw this movie and I highly suggest you see it in theatres. Don't miss the experience. I'd probably already give it the tile of best animated film of the year, shit probably the decade.

text: Good job, Disney. You actually did something right. It's been a little while.   When my older sister dragged me see this in the theaters with her, I thought it was going to be an immature movie for 3-year-olds. I was very wrong. This is one of the most mature children's films I've ever seen, and in a good way. It deals with issues like stereotyping/racism, and you've really got to credit it for that. Especially when kids my age (middle school-aged) are actually very racist, here in New York. It's a shame that they'll never see it. (If they thought Inside Out was babyish, imagine their reactions to this?) On the last few days of school, if we have time to watch a movie like we usually do, I'm definitely requesting this. The only bad thing I can say about the movie is that one portion that kinda made me cringe. (The "Naturalist Club", did they call it? I think so.) But that part was only like, 7 minutes out of the entire thing. The rest was wonderful.   This is something you NEED to show people, or see yourself.

text: This movie is EXACTLY like Tangled. Cute and innocent girl meets charming and smug criminal. The Girl, who's dream is to got to the big city, employs the dude who she has dirt on to assist them in accomplishing her goal while the their superior watches disapprovingly. They FINALLY warm up to one another after saving each other's lives and soon establish an unbreakable bond. However, a horrible misunderstanding takes place and the two friends part ways. Later, the two reunite to defeat the villian in the story and fall in love. The story concludes with the guy having all charges against him dropped after saving and helping the girl become a symbol of hope for the population. But who cares, Zootopia was still freaking awesome.

text: Just wanted to take a moment to profusely thank the folks at Disney--this was EXCELLENT!¬† From the perfectly captured awe and sheer joy communicated through Judy's expressions as she first enters Zootopia to the fabulous references and jokes/puns sprinkled through out, it was top-notch end to end.¬† I thoroughly enjoyed it.¬† I was especially impressed by the¬†amazing detail put into each character's fur¬†and the general lighting/background.¬† With such an engaging story, it's easy to miss¬†how much attention was paid to the minute and/or secondary aspects of each scene.¬† Thank you, thank you, thank you!¬† I can't wait to see more Zootopia...and find out¬†what did Nick did with all the money he supposedly made over the years....¬† Pleeeeeeeease send us an invitation to the Hopps/Wilde wedding in 2020 or so!

It's right on the precipice of $1 billion, only the 11th one by Disney, and 26th overall to reach that mmilestone. The run this movie has had is just incredible. text: Not too happy about this movie, this bunny after graduating feels entitled, feels like the world owes her everything she wanted simply because she graduated. In the real world, College/University don't mean much when it comes to the industry itself, things are always different and although your education will help you - there is still a lot to learn.   There is something called working your way up - for example in my field as an Aviation Mechanic - as a graduate you don't just start tearing apart turbines on day 1, just like this bunny or any graduated individual shouldn't be doing the most complex of tasks from day 1 - I cleaned and did tiny jobs for over 3 months before doing bigger jobs involving flight controls, etc.  Just as "Hops" here has to be a meter maid for a little while to see how she works, her job ethic, how she gets along with others, etc - its a test to see what kind of person you are before they start assigning you bigger and more important jobs.  Whereas this movie makes little chicky poo here an entitled bitch who pushes herself up through the ranks by force. But because its a Disney movie she ultimately comes out successful due to an astonishingly large amount of luck.

text: This movie was a example of Disney managing to squeeze the little bit of talent they had left into one movie. One of the movies from this year wasn't the best one (The Good Dinosaur) and this one was the good one. I loved the story and the characters. Something i noticed was how Judies ears have different positions depending on her mood. And the buildings and areas are also very creative. I would almost say this movie aimed for a adult audience, cuz it is pretty deep. There where practically no stupid songs or dead parents cliches like the most¬†Disney Movies have, and the biggest part is the animation that manages to make this movie look like a piece of art. The characters: Good. Animation: Good. Effort put into this: 10/10 and 5 stars

text: I remember thinking that this movie would be fucking awful, its trailers annoyed me when i went to see other movies such as Deadpool..  That was in March. I remember being bored and so decided to watch this "Zootopia" movie. I thought "Well, lets see how bad this shit is"  So i saw it.. and I actually liked it I don't know what i liked about it, I simply did.. I actually saw it for a second time, researched about the voice actors, back stories, deleted scenes, all sort of deleted content.. I started to realize I was obsessed with a movie I once thought would be total trash. This movie got me hooked for more than 1 and a half month, I still am.. a little. I actually drew some characters, something that I hated.. drawing.. I thought to myself " Wtf am i doing?" I tried all kinds of stuff to get the thoughts about it off me, but nothing helped. I also annoyed the heck out of one of my classmates to see it, i don't know why. So yeah.. Really good movie.  I guess.. uh.. Never judge a book by its cover..?

text: Unpopular opinion. I really didn't like this movie. I felt the plot was at times, forced as well as Judy and Nick's relationship. A friendship that has been done TO DEATH. One friend fights with the other friend, and they drift apart, only to get back together 20-30 minutes later. It has been done in Wreck-It-Ralph, and in Toy Story 1 and 2. The final showdown in the museum felt really anticlimactic. I mean, really? That was it? Also the message of "you can be anything if you just try" has also been done to death. If you would like to argue please reply, just don't be a douchehead about it.

text: The film is called Zootopia. It's an animation. I thought that it was a simple animation, but to my surprise, it wasn't. The film talks about a bunny called Judy Hobbs and a fox named Nick Wilde. The bunny's dream was to become a cop in the capital, but she didn't know what problems and adventures she was getting involved with.¬†In my opinion, the best part about the movie was the music. There was a lot of music in the movie from many famous artists. I also loved the special effects and the ending.¬†In my opinion it's worth to watch the movie. It was gripping, moving and gave me a lot to think about. The film is suitable for all ages.

text: This movie is absolutely phenomenal, I'm rewatching it now and I love how they tackled all sorts of societal issues that are happening and have been happening in the human society for a very very long time. I'm glad they used non-human animals to use as a reference to racial issues, it's only such a shame that they didn't actually state that the concept of instinct doesn't exist. I'm super glad that they worked on the concept that explains that it is not the case of aggression or someone turning into a mindless monster, but totally missed the opportunity to point out that instinct is, with all due respect, bullshit. You see, now that I'm rewatching the movie with much more knowledge after studying animal cognition, behaviour, sentience, intelligence, etc for years, it is not the concept of instinct that drives animals forward, including us - it's intelligence. It's conscious thought, rationalising, personal choices and the desire to enjoy yourself. Every organism that exists is based on intelligence. Even individual cells contain code that's intelligence, and plants are capable of thought too. The biota of Earth, especially eukaryotic beings, are all incredibly complex organisms capable of complex thought and sense of self, it's just that the perception of life of each individual is different. Carnivores are specialised in using their intelligence for tactical hunts while herbivores are specialised in security and foraging. I could go on and write you a lengthy essay on how cognition works but let's just summarize it: we are animals and other animals are people; not a wild take, it's fact and scientists have done thousands of researches that confirm exactly that. "Instinct" is just a completely dumb term used to describe a misunderstood concept of complex cognitive abilities of non-human organisms, and intelligence and comprehension that they genetically and physically have, but each action they make is based on personal choice.   So, with that said, I can't wait for the sequel. Love this movie. :^)
